Conclusion:
•Device was capable of following paths, with a method which can be used to find new PID
values for new prototypes.
•Impact resistance was tested in Solidworks and ANSYS, simulations showed small plastic
deformation, suggesting a different material or soft shell outside may be necessary
•A functioning feedback system using sound and screens was created to engage the user,
along with a menu for startup controlled by a single button for ease of use
•Storage capabilities added to arduino for storing patient performance data
•User interface and idata reading created for mobile app
•Created program utilizing machine learning and image processing to isolate faces from an
image

All of the code we wrote for our protoypes and tests was stored
and maintained in our Github repository, the link to which can
be found using the QR code on the left. The code we wrote was
used to control different sensors and components utilizing the
Arduino platform, app interface design using Xcode, and facial
recognition using tensor flow
Github
A menu to select different functions within our device
was created, as well as a way to navigate it using a
button. Additionally, success and failure animations,
figures depicting performance results, and audio
based feedback were created. These are necessary for
the user to navigate the device, to keep the patient
engaged, and display messages to the user.
An app that is capable of visualizing data collected
from the multiple sensors installed on the device via
bluetooth. This visual will show the physician the
patient progress throughout the session.

Problem: Stroke rehabilitation of the upper
extremities is a tedious and arduous process, which
involves repetitive reach exercises, which patients
must keep up with, or they risk permanent loss of
motor control
Need:
In order to make reach exercises more engaging for
stroke patients, we will create a small robot, which follows
a path drawn by a physician on a piece of paper. While
following this path, the device will prompt the patient to
reach out and interact with the device, give feedback along
Constraints:
Device must be visually
appealing/friendly to the user, engaging, small (about
the size of a softball), and capable of resisting falls
from 1 meter
